# Approach 1: use a set and sweep

The approach for the following variants is always the same. We the list of banned
numbers into a data structure that's faster to access and then we sweep the numbers
from 1 to n while the sum is blow `maxSum`.

## Variant 1: std::set (525 ms)

We can directly construct the set from the input vector.

```cpp
    static int maxCount(const vector<int>& banned_vector, const int n, const int maxSum) {
        set<int> banned(begin(banned_vector), end(banned_vector));

        int sum = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            if (sum + i > maxSum) break;

            if (banned.count(i)) continue;

            sum += i;
            ++ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

## Variant 2: std::set, only insert numbers <= n (329 ms)

Not inserting all the numbers yields a nice speedup.

```cpp
    static int maxCount(const vector<int>& banned_vector, const int n, const int maxSum) {
        set<int> banned;
        for (int b : banned_vector)
            if (b <= n) banned.insert(b);

        int sum = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            if (sum + i > maxSum) break;

            if (banned.count(i)) continue;

            sum += i;
            ++ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

## Variant 3: std::unordered_set (253 ms)

Using a hash set instead of an ordered set yields and anther nice speedup.

```cpp
    static int maxCount(const vector<int>& banned_vector, const int n, const int maxSum) {
        unordered_set<int> banned;
        for (int b : banned_vector)
            if (b <= n) banned.insert(b);

        int sum = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            if (sum + i > maxSum) break;

            if (banned.count(i)) continue;

            sum += i;
            ++ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

## Variant 4: set::bitset (138 ms)

The number range in the ```banned``` vector is quite limited, so we can use a ```std::bitset``` instead of a hash set, which gives us a nice speedup as well.

```cpp
    static int maxCount(const vector<int>& banned_vector, const int n, const int maxSum) {
        bitset<10240> banned;
        for (int b : banned_vector)
            if (b <= n) banned[b] = true;

        int sum = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            if (sum + i > maxSum) break;

            if (banned[i]) continue;

            sum += i;
            ++ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

# Approach 2: sort and sweep (225ms)

Instead of using an extra set we can sort the banned vector so we can sweep it easily too. The sweep code feels bit clumbsy, please let me know if you have a nicer approach.

```cpp
    static int maxCount(vector<int>& banned, const int n, const int maxSum) {
        sort(begin(banned), end(banned));

        int sum = 0;
        int ans = 0;
        int b = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            if (sum + i > maxSum) break;

            if (b < size(banned)) {
                while (b < size(banned) && banned[b] < i) ++b;

                if (b < size(banned) && banned[b] == i) continue;
            }

            sum += i;
            ++ans;
        }
        return ans;
    }
```

