# C++ Code | Using Sorting
# Complexity
- Time complexity: if m = banned.size()-
- m(logm) for sorting the array ```banned``` and
- O(n) for tarversing 1 to n
- So ```overall Time Complexity``` : O( m(logm) + n )
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: As I have not used any extra space so, 
- ```Space Complexity``` : O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxCount(vector<int>& banned, int n, int maxSum) {
        int m = banned.size();
        sort(banned.begin(), banned.end());
        int j = 0; //iterate through banned array
        int i = 1;
        int ans = 0;
        int sum = 0;
        while(i <= n){
            if(j < m && i == banned[j]){
                while(j < m && i == banned[j]) j++;
            }
            else{
                sum += i;
                if(sum <= maxSum) ans++;
                else break;
            }
            i++;
        }
        return ans;  
    }
};
```
