# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It can avoid travesing over 1 to n with each pair of [i-1, i], the sum of [a1,an] is cnt*(a1 + an) / 2, so we only need to traverse over [a1,an] at the last part of numbers
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxCount(vector<int>& banned, int n, int maxSum) {
        sort(banned.begin(), banned.end());    
        if (banned.back() <= n)
            banned.push_back(n + 1);
        int sum = 0, ans = 0, prev = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < banned.size(); ++i) {
            int a1 = prev + 1, an = min(n, banned[i] - 1);
            prev = banned[i];
            if (a1 > an)
                continue;
            int cnt = an - a1 + 1, total = cnt * (an + a1) / 2;
            if (total + sum <= maxSum) {
                ans += cnt;
                sum += total;
            } else {
                while (a1 <= an) {
                    if (a1 + sum <= maxSum) {
                        sum += a1;
                        ans++;
                    }
                    a1++;
                }
                return ans;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

